                    <div class='commenttext'><span class="comment-author"><strong><span style="font-size: 120%;">#89 Fiona</span></strong> @ 6:28 am May 13th, 2008</span><br />
<p>Porridge is not only an economical way to break your fast (plain oats cooked on the stove top in less than 5 minutes while making the lunches, feeding the cat, drying your hair &#8230;), the savings extend into the day. You&#8217;ll be satisfied until lunchtime and won&#8217;t need a mid morning snack. My father always added a good amount of salt in homage to his Scottish forebears but I like a little soft brown sugar instead. In my experience, the stovetop method produces good thick porridge. If you are pressed for time, soaking the oats in water overnight softens them before cooking in the morning and reduces the cooking time. Eating porridge (as I&#8217;ve done since childhood), even with some sugar, makes prepared and packaged breakfast cereals taste too sweet to me. This includes those which are marketed as healthy alternatives. As these other cereals are generally much more expensive than porridge made from scratch at home, I&#8217;m feeling very good on multiple levels about getting my oats.</p>
